{"id":8923,"date":"2019-11-01T14:48:34","date_gmt":"2019-11-01T14:48:34","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/?p=8923"},"modified":"2020-09-02T09:52:41","modified_gmt":"2020-09-02T09:52:41","slug":"factsmatter-fact-checking-training-for-media-practitioners-in-juba-south-sudan","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/factsmatter-fact-checking-training-for-media-practitioners-in-juba-south-sudan\/","title":{"rendered":"#FactsMatter: Fact-checking Training for Media Practitioners in Juba, South Sudan"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<p><strong>Defy Hate Now <\/strong>in partnership with the <a href=\"http:\/\/www.unesco.org\/new\/en\/juba\/\">UNESCO Office in Juba<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/justiceafrica.org\/\">Justice Africa<\/a> held a two-day fact-checking training with journalists and content creators on the 15th and 16th of October, 2019. This was the first of Defy Hate Now-led series of trainings on fact-checking, which will take place in the next couple of months.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-1 is-cropped\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1200\" height=\"800\" src=\"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/5Q7A4065-1200x800.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"8925\" data-link=\"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/?attachment_id=8925\" class=\"wp-image-8925\" srcset=\"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/5Q7A4065-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/5Q7A4065-744x496.jpg 744w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/5Q7A4065-768x512.jpg 768w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/5Q7A4065-580x387.jpg 580w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/5Q7A4065-860x573.jpg 860w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/5Q7A4065-1160x773.jpg 1160w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px\" \/><figcaption>Doreen Loboka from <a href=\"http:\/\/www.unesco.org\/new\/en\/juba\/\">UNESCO in Juba<\/a> giving her opening address<\/figcaption><\/figure><\/li><\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>This training brought together over thirty participants; a group of enthusiastic South Sudanese journalists from various media houses and content creators who are keen on furthering good journalism by publishing verified information.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>The training was led by&nbsp; trainers from Kenya and South Sudan, who are well versed in journalism and blogging. Over the two days, the team took the media practitioners through the importance of fact-checking and&nbsp; how it impacts the consumption of news in South Sudan and the world, and the necessary tools needed.<br><\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1200\" height=\"548\" src=\"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/20191016_110944-1200x548.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8929\" srcset=\"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/20191016_110944-1200x548.jpg 1200w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/20191016_110944-744x340.jpg 744w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/20191016_110944-768x351.jpg 768w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/20191016_110944-580x265.jpg 580w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/20191016_110944-860x393.jpg 860w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/20191016_110944-1160x530.jpg 1160w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px\" \/><figcaption>The trainers &#8211; James Wamathai, Kendi Gikunda and Nelson Kwaje<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>This training was informed by a <a href=\"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/south-sudan-fake-news\/\">survey<\/a> by Defy Hate Now where more than 50% of our respondents said that Social Media and blogs are their primary sources of information in South Sudan. The country has seen a huge growth in the number of citizens who consume online information, despite the low internet connectivity in the country. However, this growth in online information consumption was not accompanied by a similar growth in the number and quality of online information sources in the country.&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1200\" height=\"675\" src=\"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/08\/1-20-copy-2560x1440-1200x675.jpeg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8770\" srcset=\"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/08\/1-20-copy-2560x1440-1200x675.jpeg 1200w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/08\/1-20-copy-2560x1440-744x419.jpeg 744w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/08\/1-20-copy-2560x1440-768x432.jpeg 768w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/08\/1-20-copy-2560x1440-580x326.jpeg 580w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/08\/1-20-copy-2560x1440-860x484.jpeg 860w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/08\/1-20-copy-2560x1440-1160x653.jpeg 1160w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px\" \/><figcaption> <a href=\"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/south-sudan-fake-news\/#group-explore-data-QtpDQA0XZ4\">Research by Defy Hate Now, in collaboration with Data4Change and Small Media Foundation<\/a> <\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>With this in mind, some of the&nbsp; important topics that were covered in the course of the training included Misinformation and Fake News in South Sudan, fact-checking tools and strategies, and alternative media &amp; its challenges.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>To further understand the concept of misinformation, disinformation and mal-information, the&nbsp; participants discussed and analyzed some of the stories which were controversial in South Sudan, such as the alleged death of President Salva Kiir in 2016, and the <a href=\"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/photo-of-a-lady-named-atong-james-is-fake\/\">photo of a lady named Atong James<\/a> who was allegedly tortured and killed by the National Security.<br><\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1200\" height=\"800\" src=\"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/5Q7A4297-1200x800.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8928\" srcset=\"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/5Q7A4297-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/5Q7A4297-744x496.jpg 744w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/5Q7A4297-768x512.jpg 768w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/5Q7A4297-580x387.jpg 580w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/5Q7A4297-860x573.jpg 860w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/5Q7A4297-1160x773.jpg 1160w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px\" \/><figcaption>Group Discussion<\/figcaption><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Additionally, the participants spent the better part of the second day fact-checking some of the chapters in the 2018 South Sudan Peace Agreement, and they committed to doing a deeper analysis then publish the reports, with the support of Defy Hate Now.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>This group will be part of the newly formed South Sudan Fact-checkers Network, an initiative will bring together media practitioners from Juba and other regions to collaborate and produce more factual and verified reports with the Defy Hate Now&#8217;s financial and editorial help.\u00a0<br><br><\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1200\" height=\"540\" src=\"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/20191016_110717-1200x540.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8932\" srcset=\"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/20191016_110717-1200x540.jpg 1200w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/20191016_110717-744x335.jpg 744w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/20191016_110717-768x346.jpg 768w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/20191016_110717-580x261.jpg 580w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/20191016_110717-860x387.jpg 860w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/20191016_110717-1160x522.jpg 1160w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1200\" height=\"800\" src=\"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/5Q7A4347-1-1200x800.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8933\" srcset=\"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/5Q7A4347-1-1200x800.jpg 1200w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/5Q7A4347-1-744x496.jpg 744w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/5Q7A4347-1-768x512.jpg 768w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/5Q7A4347-1-580x387.jpg 580w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/5Q7A4347-1-860x573.jpg 860w, https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2019\/11\/5Q7A4347-1-1160x773.jpg 1160w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>\u201cThank you Defy Hate Now for giving me the opportunity to interact with such great, fresh minds.&nbsp; I am pleased and honoured to be part of this educative training.  It was amazing how we teamed up and fact-checked some of the fake news,\u201dsaid Rebecca Akuol, a Public Relations practitioner.<br><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>About Facts Matter<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Facts Matter is a Defy Hate Now led project that aims at enhancing the quality of online information sharing through fact-checking and information verification. Since June 2019, the organization has been verifying and demystifying news and information shared on public platforms through data stories and visualizations.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Defy Hate Now is facilitating trainings on fact-checking for media practitioners, Civil Society Organizations and governments, where they will be taught the trends in fake news technology, methodologies for managing fake news, and fact-checking tools.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Defy Hate Now in partnership with the UNESCO Office in Juba and Justice Africa held a two-day fact-checking training with journalists and content creators on the 15th and 16th of [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":8941,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":[],"categories":[167,9,14],"tags":[],"yoast_head":"<!-- This site is optimized with the Yoast SEO plugin v15.2.1 - https:\/\/yoast.com\/wordpress\/plugins\/seo\/ -->\n<title>#FactsMatter: Fact-checking Training for Media Practitioners in Juba, South Sudan - #defyhatenow<\/title>\n<meta name=\"robots\" content=\"index, follow, max-snippet:-1, max-image-preview:large, max-video-preview:-1\" \/>\n<link rel=\"canonical\" href=\"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/factsmatter-fact-checking-training-for-media-practitioners-in-juba-south-sudan\/\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:locale\" content=\"en_US\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:type\" content=\"article\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:title\" content=\"#FactsMatter: Fact-checking Training for Media Practitioners in Juba, South Sudan - #defyhatenow\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:description\" content=\"Defy Hate Now in partnership with the UNESCO Office in Juba and Justice Africa held a two-day fact-checking training with journalists and content creators on the 15th and 16th of [&hellip;]\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:url\" content=\"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/factsmatter-fact-checking-training-for-media-practitioners-in-juba-south-sudan\/\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:site_name\" content=\"#defyhatenow\" \/>\n<meta property=\"article:published_time\" content=\"2019-11-01T14:48:34+00:00\" \/>\n<meta property=\"article:modified_time\" content=\"2020-09-02T09:52:41+00:00\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:image\" content=\"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/